The paper introduces a novel privacy framework that leverages generative adversarial networks (GANs) to learn privatization schemes from the dataset itself. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper mentions information theoretic privacy (cs.IT) and statistical dataset models (cs.DS), indicating that these sub-categories are also relevant. Finally, the paper uses game theory to derive optimal privacy mechanisms, which suggests that the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category may also be relevant.
